article.description:
Penny Taylor led five Phoenix players in double figures with 23 points, and the host Mercury snapped Sacramento's
seven-game winning streak, 76-62 Friday night.
article.headline: Taylor leads balanced Phoenix attack
article.linkText: Mercury snap Monarchs' win streak at seven
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- The Phoenix Mercury were more pleased with
beating the first-place Sacramento Monarchs than with getting to
.500 after a 3-11 start.

Penny Taylor led five Phoenix players in double figures with 23
points, and the Mercury snapped the Sacramento Monarchs' seven-game
winning streak, 76-62 Friday night.

"It just boosts your confidence," Taylor said. "It just shows
us that the things we are doing are the right things and we will
continue to play that way. It's a little more mental for them that
they know we could be facing each other in the first round of the
playoffs and we can get the job done."

Maria Stepanova and Anna DeForge each had 14 points for Phoenix
(13-13), which has won 10 of 12. Stepanova added seven rebounds and
four blocked shots, and DeForge had five assists.

The Mercury moved 1½ games ahead of Minnesota for the fourth and
final playoff spot in the Western Conference, and within one game
of third-place Houston.

"We said before the game we wanted to make a statement about
whether we are a legitimate playoff team," Phoenix coach Carrie
Graf said. "I think the psychology of a win like that is that we
just beat the best team in the West."

Nicole Powell scored 20 points, 17 in the first half, for
first-place Sacramento (20-8), which won nine of its previous 11.
The Monarchs lead second-place Seattle by four games and have
already clinched a playoff berth.

"We had our worst game of the year tonight," Sacramento coach
John Whisenant said. "We did everything on defense that we talked
about not doing. Our defense identifies us, and it totally broke
down tonight."

The Mercury made nine of their first 12 shots to jump out to a
23-16 lead, and stretched their advantage to 49-35 by halftime. It
was Phoenix's highest scoring first half of the season.

Sacramento never got closer than 12 in the second half.

"It was very key for us to set the tone early," DeForge said.
"We shot the ball well and attacked their pressure defense and
defensively we blocked them out. We limited their second chance
points and that's part of their offense is their rebounding."

DeForge said the Mercury were focused on stopping Powell in the
second half.

"We made some defensive switches on her," DeForge said. "She
was beating us a little bit, obviously in the first half, she was
getting some easy looks. We just changed it up in the second half
and made a point to always know where she was on the floor."

Leading scorer Diana Taurasi bruised her right knee driving for
a missed shot on the final play of the first half and did not play
in the second half. She injured the knee earlier this season and
sat out one game.
